:::summary
Formal logic is the study of the principles governing correct reasoning — the rules by which conclusions follow necessarily from premises. From Aristotle's syllogistic through the medieval *logica* of the universities to the mathematical logic of Frege and Russell, formal logic has been both a foundational discipline of mathematics and a primary tool of Christian theology. Theologians have used logical inference to argue for the existence of God, to systematize doctrine, and to test the consistency of belief — and the great logical treatises of the Western tradition emerged largely within Christian educational institutions.
